          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how sensitive the result is to the discount rate — a 1% change swings the value significantly. This is why we disclose our exact assumptions.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pipeline Successes:</strong> Treatments like Casgevy (sickle cell) and suzetrigine (non-opioid pain) could ramp up faster than expected, drastically outperforming our 10% cash flow growth assumption.</li>
    <li><strong>Share Buybacks:</strong> If Vertex continues its aggressive share repurchase program, the outstanding share count will drop, pushing per-share value higher than this static model projects.</li>
    <li><strong>M&A Value:</strong> Vertex could use its $6.6B in cash and short-term investments to acquire entirely new growth verticals that aren't modeled here.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Patent Cliffs:</strong> While Trikafta's patents extend into the late 2030s, any unexpected legal challenges to its IP would devastate future cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Pipeline Failures:</strong> Developing new drugs is incredibly expensive. If new candidates fail in phase 3 trials, billions of dollars of R&D expenses go un-recouped, destroying FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing Pressure:</strong> Government legislation (e.g., Inflation Reduction Act) or pushback from European health authorities could force Vertex to lower the price of its therapies, squeezing its massive operating margins.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. During bubbles, P/E ratios are high; during panics, they're low. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 9% discount rate and not 7% or 11%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. For a company with Vertex's stable cash flow, a 9% WACC provides a balanced premium that recognizes the general risks of biotech while rewarding the company for its entrenched market position.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why was FCF negative in 2024?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Vertex's cash flow in 2024 was heavily impacted by in-process research and development (IPR&D) expenses and upfront payments for licensing deals and acquisitions. This is standard in the pharmaceutical industry as companies reinvest cash into their pipelines to secure future growth.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

